re, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","England":"England","Huntingdon, Huntingdonshire, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom":"Huntingdon, Huntingdonshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Huntingtondonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Huntingdon, Huntingdonshire, England":"Huntingdon, Huntingdonshire, England","Huntingdonshire, England":"Huntingdonshire, England"},"en":{"1433–1503":"1433–1503","1433–1490":"1433–1490","1462–1548":"1462–1548","1463–1508":"1463–1508","1466–Female":"1466–Deceased","1412–1482":"1412–1482","1417–Female":"1417–Deceased","1503":"1503","1412":"1412","1433":"1433","1466":"1466","Abt 1462":"about 1462","1463":"1463","1462":"1462","1482":"1482","1508":"1508","1490":"1490","1417":"1417","1548":"1548","Huntingdon, Huntingdonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Huntingdon, Huntingdonshire, England, United Kingdom","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","England":"England","Huntingdon, Huntingdonshire, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom":"Huntingdon, Huntingdonshire, England, United Kingdom","Huntingtondonshire, England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","Huntingdon, Huntingdonshire, England":"Huntingdon, Huntingdonshire, England","Huntingdonshire, England":"Huntingdonshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Huntingdon","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Huntington  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Huntington","meanings":["English (northern): habitational name from any of various places called Huntington, most of which are named with Old English <i>huntena</i>, the genitive plural form of <i>hunta</i> ‘hunter, huntsman’, + <i>dūn</i> ‘hill’ or <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. Some, however, may have Old English <i>hunting</i> ‘hunting’ as the initial element, while others may derive from the Old English personal name <i>Hunta</i> (genitive <i>Huntan</i>), perhaps with Old English connective <i>-ing-</i>, + <i>tūn</i>. The surname may also arise from Huntingdon (Huntingdonshire), which derives from the Old English personal name <i>Hunta</i> (genitive <i>Huntan</i>) or Old English <i>hunta</i> (genitive <i>huntan</i>) + <i>dūn</i>.","History: A prominent American family of this name were founded by Simon Huntington, who himself never saw the New World, for he died in 1633 on the voyage to Boston, where his widow settled with her children. Their descendants include Jabez Huntington (1719–86), a wealthy West Indies trader, and Samuel Huntington (1731–96), who was one of the signers of the Declaration of Independence. Collis Potter Huntington (1821–1900) was an American railway magnate. Beginning with little education or money, he made a huge fortune, some of which he left to his nephew, Henry Huntington (1850–1927), who used the money to establish the Huntington library and art gallery in CA."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret De Huntingdon was born in 1433, in 